{"title_page": "Omelek Island", "text_new": "<!-- {{Launching/Falcon|type=launch site|role=support a launch}}\nPlease re-enable this template when the next Falcon launch will be from Omelek.\n-->\n{{Coord|9|2|52.30|N|167|44|34.80|E|display=title}}\n[[Image:Omelek Island.jpg|right|thumb|Aerial view]]\n'''Omelek Island''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|m|\u0259l|\u025b|k}}; [[Marshallese language|Marshallese]]: '''{{lang|mh|Kom\u0327le}}''', pronounced {{IPAc-mh|kw&mhl&y}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trussel2.com/MOD/LocK.htm#Kuwajleen |title=Marshallese-English Dictionary - Place Name Index |publisher=Trussel2.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> is part of the [[Kwajalein|Kwajalein Atoll]] in the [[Marshall Islands|Republic of the Marshall Islands]]. It is controlled by the [[United States military]] under a long-term lease (along with ten other islands in the [[atoll]]) and is part of the [[Ronald Reagan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Island is about {{convert|32000|sqm|acre}} in size.  Geologically, it is composed of [[reef|reef-rock]], as are the other islands in the atoll, which is created by the accumulation of marine organism remnants ([[coral]]s, [[Mollusca]], etc.)\n\n==History==\n{{update section|date=October 2018}}\n[[Image:Kawajalein Omelek.png|right|thumb|Map of Kwajalein Atoll]]\nOmelek has long been used by the [[United States]] for small research [[rocket launch]]es due to its relative isolation in the South Pacific.  The last U.S. government rocket launch occurred in 1996.\n\nAfter 2000, the island's [[equator]]ial proximity and nearby radar tracking infrastructure attracted [[SpaceX]], an [[orbital spaceflight|orbital]] launch provider, which updated facilities on the island and established it as their primary launch location by 2006. SpaceX began launching [[Falcon 1]] rockets from Omelek in 2006. [[Falcon 1 Flight 4]], the first successful [[Private spaceflight|privately funded]], [[Liquid-propellant rocket|liquid-propelled]] orbital [[launch vehicle]], was launched from Omelek Island on 28 September 2008 and was followed by another Falcon 1 launch on 13 July 2009, placing [[RazakSAT]] into orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon/005/status.html |title=Falcon Launch Report &#124; Mission Status Center |publisher=Spaceflight Now |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> This 2009 flight was the last flight of Falcon 1, and it also became the last flight of SpaceX from Omelek.\n\nIn total, SpaceX launched 5 rockets (all Falcon 1s) from Omelek between 2006 and 2009, with two successes (28 September 2008, 14 July 2009) and three (24 March 2006, 21 March 2007, 3 August 2008) failures.\n\nOmelek was planned to host launches for the upgraded [[Falcon 1e]] rocket,<ref name=gsc20130919>\n{{cite web |title=Falcon-1e|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau_det/falcon-1e.htm |work=Gunter's Space Page |publisher=skyrocket.de |accessdate=2013-12-06 |date=2013-09-19 }}</ref><ref name=slr20090718>\n{{cite web |title=SpaceX Falcon Data Sheet |url=http://www.spacelaunchreport.com/falcon.html |date=2009-07-18 |publisher=Space Launch Report |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> but in 2011-2012, SpaceX stopped development on the Falcon 1e launches while it focused on its large Falcon 9 launch manifest.\n\nSpaceX had tentatively planned to upgrade the launch site for use by the [[Falcon 9]] launch vehicle. {{as of|December 2010}}, the SpaceX launch manifest listed Omelek (Kwajalein) as a potential site for several Falcon 9 launches,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2006/08/spacex-has-magical-goals-for-falcon-9/|title=SpaceX has magical goals for Falcon 9|date=August 6, 2006}}</ref> the first in 2012,<ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\">{{cite web|title=Launch Manifest|url=http://www.spacex.com/launch_manifest.php|publisher=SpaceX|accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref> and the Falcon 9 Overview document offered Kwajalein as a launch option.<ref name=SxLaunchCost20101206>{{cite web|url=http://www.spacex.com/falcon9.php#pricing_and_performance| title=Falcon 9 Overview, Performance |publisher=SpaceX |date=2010 |accessdate=2010-12-28}}</ref> In any event, SpaceX did not make the upgrades necessary to support Falcon 9 launches from the atoll and did not launch Falcon 9 from Omelek.\n\nThe Reagan Test Site, which includes rocket launch sites on other islands in the Kwajalein Atoll, on [[Wake Island]], and at [[Aur Atoll]], is the only U.S. government equatorial launch facility.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Omelek}}\n*[http://www.smdcen.us/pubdocs/files/spacex_final_ea_signed_fnsi_13dec04.pdf Environmental assessment and overview of SpaceX's launch facilities at Omelek]\n\n{{SpaceX}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kwajalein Atoll]]\n[[Category:Rocket launch sites]]\n[[Category:SpaceX facilities]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Marshall Islands]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- {{Launching/Falcon|type=launch site|role=support a launch}}\nPlease re-enable this template when the next Falcon launch will be from Omelek.\n-->\n{{Coord|9|2|52.30|N|167|44|34.80|E|display=title}}\n[[Image:Omelek Island.jpg|right|thumb|Aerial view]]\n'''Omelek Island''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|o\u028a|m|\u0259l|\u025b|k}}; [[Marshallese language|Marshallese]]: '''{{lang|mh|Kom\u0327le}}''', pronounced {{IPAc-mh|kw&mhl&y}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trussel2.com/MOD/LocK.htm#Kuwajleen |title=Marshallese-English Dictionary - Place Name Index |publisher=Trussel2.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> is part of the [[Kwajalein|Kwajalein Atoll]] in the [[Marshall Islands|Republic of the Marshall Islands]]. It is controlled by the [[United States military]] under a long-term lease (along with ten other islands in the [[atoll]]) and is part of the [[Ronald Reagan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe Island is about {{convert|32000|sqm|acre}} in size.  Geologically, it is composed of [[reef|reef-rock]], as are the other islands in the atoll, which is created by the accumulation of marine organism remnants ([[coral]]s, [[Mollusca]], etc.)\n\n==History==\n{{update section|date=October 2018}}\n[[Image:Kawajalein Omelek.png|right|thumb|Map of Kwajalein Atoll]]\nOmelek has long been used by the [[United States]] for small research [[rocket launch]]es due to its relative isolation in the South Pacific.  The last U.S. government rocket launch occurred in 1996.\n\nAfter 2000, the island's [[equator]]ial proximity and nearby radar tracking infrastructure attracted [[SpaceX]], an [[orbital spaceflight|orbital]] launch provider, which updated facilities on the island and established it as their primary launch location by 2006. SpaceX began launching [[Falcon 1]] rockets from Omelek in 2006. [[Falcon 1 Flight 4]], the first successful [[Private spaceflight|privately funded]], [[Liquid-propellant rocket|liquid-propelled]] orbital [[launch vehicle]], was launched from Omelek Island on 28 September 2008 and was followed by another Falcon 1 launch on 13 July 2009, placing [[RazakSAT]] into orbit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spaceflightnow.com/falcon/005/status.html |title=Falcon Launch Report &#124; Mission Status Center |publisher=Spaceflight Now |date= |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> This 2009 flight was the last flight of Falcon 1, and it also became the last flight of SpaceX from Omelek.\n\nIn total, SpaceX launched 5 rockets (all Falcon 1s) from Omelek between 2006 and 2009, with two successes (28 September 2008, 14 July 2009) and three (24 March 2006, 21 March 2007, 3 August 2008) failures.\n\nOmelek was planned to host launches for the upgraded [[Falcon 1e]] rocket,<ref name=gsc20130919>\n{{cite web |title=Falcon-1e|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_lau_det/falcon-1e.htm |work=Gunter's Space Page |publisher=skyrocket.de |accessdate=2013-12-06 |date=2013-09-19 }}</ref><ref name=slr20090718>\n{{cite web |title=SpaceX Falcon Data Sheet |url=http://www.spacelaunchreport.com/falcon.html |date=2009-07-18 |publisher=Space Launch Report |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> but in 2011-2012, SpaceX stopped development on the Falcon 1e launches while it focused on its large Falcon 9 launch manifest.\n\nSpaceX had tentatively planned to upgrade the launch site for use by the [[Falcon 9]] launch vehicle. {{as of|December 2010}}, the SpaceX launch manifest listed Omelek (Kwajalein) as a potential site for several Falcon 9 launches,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2006/08/spacex-has-magical-goals-for-falcon-9/|title=SpaceX has magical goals for Falcon 9|date=August 6, 2006}}</ref> the first in 2012,<ref name=\"SpaceX Launch Manifest\">{{cite web|title=Launch Manifest|url=http://www.spacex.com/launch_manifest.php|publisher=SpaceX|accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref> and the Falcon 9 Overview document offered Kwajalein as a launch option.<ref name=SxLaunchCost20101206> {{cite web|url=http://www.spacex.com/falcon9.php#pricing_and_performance| title=Falcon 9 Overview, Performance |publisher=SpaceX |date=2010 |accessdate=2010-12-28}}</ref> In any event, SpaceX did not make the upgrades necessary to support Falcon 9 launches from the atoll and did not launch Falcon 9 from Omelek.\n\nThe Reagan Test Site, which includes rocket launch sites on other islands in the Kwajalein Atoll, on [[Wake Island]], and at [[Aur Atoll]], is the only U.S. government equatorial launch facility.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Omelek}}\n*[http://www.smdcen.us/pubdocs/files/spacex_final_ea_signed_fnsi_13dec04.pdf Environmental assessment and overview of SpaceX's launch facilities at Omelek]\n\n{{SpaceX}}\n\n[[Category:Kwajalein Atoll]]\n[[Category:Rocket launch sites]]\n[[Category:SpaceX facilities]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Marshall Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omelek_Island"}
{"title_page": "Jeff Daniels", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jeff Daniels\n| image              = Jeff Daniels May 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size         =\n| caption            = Daniels at the [[Montclair Film Festival]], May 2018''\n| birth_name         = Jeffrey Warren Daniels\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1955|2|19|}}\n| birth_place        = [[Athens, Georgia]], U.S.\n| education          = [[Central Michigan University]]\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actor\n* musician\n* playwright}}\n| children           = 3\n| website            = {{url|http://www.jeffdaniels.com}}\n| othername          =\n| yearsactive        = 1976\u2013present\n| home_town          = [[Chelsea, Michigan]], U.S.\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Kathleen Rosemary Treado|1979}}\n}}\n'''Jeffrey Warren Daniels''' (born February 19, 1955)<ref>{{cite web|title=Famous birthdays for Feb. 19: Smokey Robinson, Jeff Daniels|date=February 19, 2020|publisher=[[United Press International]]|url=https://www.upi.com/amp/Entertainment_News/2020/02/19/Famous-birthdays-for-Feb-19-Smokey-Robinson-Jeff-Daniels/7051582042519/|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref> is an American actor, musician, and playwright whose career includes roles in films, stage productions, and television, for which he has won two [[Emmy Award]]s and received several [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award|Screen Actors Guild]], and [[Tony Award]] nominations.\n\nHe made his film debut in ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]'' (1981), and amassed such additional credits as ''[[Terms of Endearment]]'' (1983), Heartburn (1986), ''[[Arachnophobia (film)|Arachnophobia]]'' (1990), ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]]'' (1993), ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]'' (1994), ''[[101 Dalmatians (1996 film)|101 Dalmatians]]'' (1996), ''[[Fly Away Home]]'' (1996), ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]'' (1998), ''[[The Hours (film)|The Hours]]'' (2002), ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]'' (2003), ''[[Good Night, and Good Luck]]'' (2005), ''[[Infamous (film)|Infamous]]'' (2006), ''[[The Lookout (2007 film)|The Lookout]]'' (2007), ''[[Looper (film)|Looper]]'' (2012), ''[[Steve Jobs (film)|Steve Jobs]]'' (2015), and ''[[The Martian (film)|The Martian]]'' (2015).\n\nDaniels is also known for playing Harry Dunne in the [[buddy film|buddy]] [[comedy film|comedy]] ''[[Dumb and Dumber]]'' (1994) and its sequel ''[[Dumb and Dumber To]]'' (2014). He received [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor]] for his performances in ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]'' (1985), ''[[Something Wild (1986 film)|Something Wild]]'' (1986), and ''[[The Squid and the Whale]]'' (2005).\n\nDaniels has also received a number of award nominations for his work on stage, including [[Tony Award]] nominations for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Best Actor]] for his roles in the plays ''[[God of Carnage]]'', ''[[Blackbird (play)|Blackbird]]'' and ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (2018 play)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]''. He is the founder and current executive director of the [[Chelsea, Michigan]]\u2013based [[Purple Rose Theatre Company]].\n\nFrom 2012 to 2014, Daniels starred as Will McAvoy in the [[HBO]] [[political drama]] series ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]'', for which he won the [[65th Primetime Emmy Awards|2013]] [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] and received [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award]] nominations. He won a second [[Primetime Emmy Award]] in [[70th Primetime Emmy Awards|2018]] for his supporting performance in the [[Netflix]] [[miniseries]] ''[[Godless (TV series)|Godless]]'' (2017) and an additional nomination that year for his leading performance as [[John P. O'Neill]] in the [[Hulu]] miniseries ''[[The Looming Tower (TV series)|The Looming Tower]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\nDaniels was born in [[Athens, Georgia]], to Marjorie J. (n\u00e9e Ferguson) and Robert Lee \"Bob\" Daniels (1929-2012).<ref>{{cite web|last=Ruggieri|first=Melissa|title=Jeff Daniels is no dummy when it comes to music|date=October 25, 2010|publisher=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|url=https://www.ajc.com/entertainment/music/jeff-daniels-dummy-when-comes-music/qzABQWm8y5qy1zEMH48hkL/amp.html|accessdate=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kaufman|first=Joanne|title=Firmly Anchored|date=June 20, 2012|publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303836404577476800419460524|accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://obits.mlive.com/obituaries/annarbor/obituary.aspx?pid=159655471|title=Robert Lee Daniels obituary|publisher=Obits.mlive.com|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lai|first=Daniel|url=http://chelsea.patch.com/articles/bob-daniels-chelsea-lumber-founder-dies-at-age-83|title=Bob Daniels, Chelsea Lumber Owner, Dies at Age 83|publisher=Chelsea.patch.com|date=September 1, 2012|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> He spent the first six weeks of his life in Georgia, where his father was then teaching,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB7C16154E7487E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=NewsBank for AJC|publisher=Nl.newsbank.com|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref> and grew up in [[Chelsea, Michigan]]. His father owned the Chelsea Lumber Company and was a one-time mayor of Chelsea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://patch.com/michigan/chelsea/bob-daniels-chelsea-lumber-founder-dies-at-age-83|title=Bob Daniels, Chelsea Lumber Owner, Dies at Age 83|website=Chelsea, MI Patch|language=en-US|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-st-jeff-daniels-newsroom-20130808-story.html|title='The Newsroom's' Jeff Daniels at home on a range of characters|website=latimes.com|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDaniels was raised [[Methodist]].<ref>[http://preview.gospelcom.net/interviews/winndixie.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061211082654/http://preview.gospelcom.net/interviews/winndixie.html|date=December 11, 2006}}</ref> He briefly attended [[Central Michigan University]] and participated in the school's theater program. In the summer of 1976, he attended the [[Eastern Michigan University]] drama school to participate in a special Bicentennial Repertory program, where he performed in ''[[The Hot l Baltimore]]'' and three other plays performed in repertoire. [[Marshall W. Mason]] was the guest director at EMU, and he invited Daniels to come to New York to work at the Circle Repertory Theatre, where he performed in ''[[Fifth of July]]'' by [[Lanford Wilson]] in the 1977\u201378 season. Daniels performed in New York in ''The Shortchanged Review'' (1979) at [[Second Stage Theatre]].<ref>http://www.americantheaterwing.com/downstagecenter/detail/jeff_daniels{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928164626/http://www.americantheaterwing.com/downstagecenter/detail/jeff_daniels |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref> It was the first show of the inaugural season for Second Stage Theatre.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stage career===\nDuring the mid 1970s through to the early 1990s, Daniels starred in a number of New York productions, on and off Broadway. On Broadway, he has appeared in [[Lanford Wilson]]'s ''Fifth of July'' (1980) alongside [[William Hurt]], for which Daniels was nominated for a [[Drama Desk Award]] for Best Supporting Actor. He also starred in [[A. R. Gurney]]'s ''The Golden Age'' (1984) with [[Stockard Channing]], and Wilson's ''[[Redwood Curtain]]'' (1993). Off-Broadway, he starred in Wilson's ''Lemon Sky'' with [[Cynthia Nixon]] where he received a Drama Desk nomination for and an [[Obie Award]] for his performance in the [[Circle Repertory Company]] production of ''[[Johnny Got His Gun]]''. Daniels appeared in an Off-Broadway production of [[David Harrower]]'s ''[[Blackbird (play)|Blackbird]]'' alongside [[Allison Pill]] whom he would later reunite with in [[Aaron Sorkin]]'s ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]''.\n\nIn 1991 Daniels founded the [[Purple Rose Theatre Company]], a nonprofit stage company in Chelsea, Michigan named after the 1985 [[Woody Allen]] movie, ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]'', which Daniels starred in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/jeff-daniels-play-nommed-for-atca-award-purple-rose-greenhouse-grows-new-plays-com-109347|title=Jeff Daniels Play Nommed for ATCA Award; Purple Rose Greenhouse Grows New Plays|website=Playbill|access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref> Daniels has written more than a dozen plays for the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jeffdaniels.com/about/about-jeff|title=About Jeff Daniels|website=Jeff Daniels|access-date=April 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, after a 16 year long absence, Daniels returned to Broadway in [[Yasmina Reza]]'s original play ''[[God of Carnage]]'' alongside [[Hope Davis]], [[James Gandolfini]], and [[Marcia Gay Harden]]. The play centers around two sets of parents who agree to meet due to a fight among their respective sons. Their meeting starts out civilized however, as the evening goes on, the parents become increasingly childish, resulting in the evening devolving into chaos. The play debuted at The [[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre]] in previews on February 28, 2009, and officially on March 22, 2009. Originally planned for a limited engagement to close July 19, 2009, the run was extended through February 28, 2010 before converting to an open-ended run. Daniels received his first [[Tony Award]] Nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play]] for his performance. The show won the [[Tony Award for Best Play]].\n\nIn 2016 Daniels returned to Broadway in the Revival of [[David Harrower]]'s ''[[Blackbird (play)|Blackbird]]'' alongside [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/blackbird-starring-jeff-daniels-and-michelle-williams-ends-broadway-run|title=Blackbird, Starring Jeff Daniels and Michelle Williams, Ends Broadway Run|last=Gans|first=Andrew|date=June 11, 2016|website=Playbill|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> The play depicts a young woman (Williams) meeting a middle-aged man (Daniels), fifteen years after being sexually abused by him when she was twelve. The play ran at the [[Belasco Theatre]] on February 5, 2016 (37 previews), and opened officially on March 10 (through June 11, 108 performances) where it was directed by [[Joe Mantello]] and received widespread critical acclaim.<ref name=\":0\" /> Daniels was nominated for his second [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Williams received a [[Tony Award]] nomination as well.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Jeff Daniels as Atticus Finch.jpg|thumb|Jeff Daniels as Atticus Finch in 2019.]]\nIn 2018, Daniels starred as [[Atticus Finch]], reuniting with [[Aaron Sorkin]] in his stage adaptation of ''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (2018 play)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]''. The play opened on Broadway at the [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theatre]]. The production began previews on November 1, 2018, prior to an official opening on December 13, 2018. During the week ending on December 23, 2018, the production grossed over $1.5 million, breaking the record for box office grosses for a non-musical play in a theater owned by [[The Shubert Organization]]. Daniels received his third [[Tony Award]] nomination for [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Best Actor in a Play]]. The show received 8 other [[Tony Award]] nominations. In June 2019, producer [[Scott Rudin]] announced that Daniels would leave the production in November 2019 and would be succeeded by [[Ed Harris]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/theater/2019/06/14/ed-harris-to-kill-a-mockingbird-aaron-sorkin/|title=Ed Harris to succeed Jeff Daniels as Atticus Finch in Broadway's 'To Kill a Mockingbird'|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Daniels' last performance was on November 3, 2019.\n\n===Film and television===\nDaniels made his screen debut in [[Milo\u0161 Forman]]'s ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]'' in 1981.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1985/04/16/jeff-daniels-coming-up-roses/9657b368-f438-4ce8-87d0-8c560827af8c/|title=Jeff Daniels, Coming Up Roses|last=Mansfield|first=Stephanie|date=April 16, 1985|work=Washington Post|access-date=April 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> His next film was in [[James L. Brooks]]\u2019s ''[[Terms of Endearment]],'' which won the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]]. The film follows an emotional relationship between mother ([[Shirley MacLaine]]) and daughter ([[Debra Winger]]). Daniels plays  Winger's callow and unfaithful husband, a role which would prove to be his breakthrough.<ref>https://www.wzzm13.com/article/news/local/michigan/jeff-daniels-to-hollywood-if-you-want-me-ill-be-in-michigan/69-527634947</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Daniels starred in [[Woody Allen]]\u2019s ''[[Purple Rose of Cairo|The Purple Rose Of Cairo]]'' alongside [[Mia Farrow]] and [[Danny Aiello]]. The film was met with critical praise earning a 91% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with the consensus reading, \"lighthearted and sweet, ''Purple Rose'' stands as one of Woody Allen's more inventive \u2013 and enchantingly whimsical \u2013 pictures.\"<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/purple_rose_of_cairo</ref> Daniels garnered a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe nomination]] for his performance<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcall.com/entertainment/lehigh-valley-music/mc-interviewing-jeff-daniels-of-newsroom-dumb-and-dumber-guitar-started-as-distraction-became-2nd-care-20150507-column.html|title=Interviewing Jeff Daniels of 'Newsroom,' 'Dumb and Dumber': Guitar started as distraction, became 2nd career|last=Moser|first=John J.|date=May 7, 2015|work=The Morning Call|access-date=April 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> It was the film that inspired the name for the theater company he established.<ref name=\"Detroit: Theater\">{{Cite web|url=http://artsamerica.org/detroit/theater|title=Detroit: Theater|website=Arts America|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, he starred in [[Jonathan Demme]]'s ''[[Something Wild (1986 film)|Something Wild]]'' as an unassuming businessman swept up into a wild night by a mysterious woman ([[Melanie Griffith]]) and earned his second [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe nomination]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001099/awards</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Daniels starred in two films (''[[Love Hurts (1991 film)|Love Hurts]]'' and ''[[The Butcher's Wife]]''). His next notable role was as Colonel [[Joshua Chamberlain]] in ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]].'' Daniels reprised the role of Chamberlain 10 years later in the prequel film ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ehistory.osu.edu/articles/interview-jeff-daniels-writer-director-actor\u2026and-student-civil-war|title=An Interview with Jeff Daniels Writer, Director, Actor....and Student of the Civil War|last=Largent|first=Kimberly|date=February 2003|website=osu.edu|publisher=Ohio State University Department of History|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 Daniels would co-star with [[Jim Carrey]] in one of his most commercially successful films, ''[[Dumb and Dumber]]''. It was a noted departure for Daniels, owing to his status as a dramatic actor. That same year Daniels appeared with [[Keanu Reeves]] in the action blockbuster ''[[Speed (1994 film)|Speed]]''; the film was an enormous hit, grossing over $350 million at the box office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=speed.htm|title=Speed (1994) \u2013 Box Office Mojo|website=www.boxofficemojo.com|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDaniels would then host ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' a second time before the release of the 1996 [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] live-action remake of ''[[101 Dalmatians (1996 film)|101 Dalmatians]].'' Daniels starred as the owner of a litter of dalmatians stolen by the evil [[Cruella De Vil]] ([[Glenn Close]]). The film was successful, grossing $320 million. Also in 1996 was the family hit film ''[[Fly Away Home]]'' with Daniels as the supportive single father of [[Anna Paquin]]'s goose-raising preteen. Daniels then had a critical and commercial misfire with ''[[Trial and Error (1997 film)|Trial and Error]]'' (1997). He would rebound, however, with 1998's ''[[Pleasantville (film)|Pleasantville]]'' as diner owner Bill Johnson, who learns to act as an individual and rebel against the norm at the urging of [[Tobey Maguire]]'s David. Also starring [[Reese Witherspoon]], [[Joan Allen]], and [[Don Knotts]], ''Pleasantville'' was nominated for three Academy Awards. Daniels starred alongside [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the critically and commercially unsuccessful film, ''[[My Favorite Martian (film)|My Favorite Martian]]''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Petrie|first=Donald|title=My Favorite Martian|date=February 12, 1999|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120764|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDaniels starred in the TV films ''[[The Crossing (2000 film)|The Crossing]]'', ''[[Cheaters (2000 film)|Cheaters]]'', and the direct-to-video release ''[[Chasing Sleep]]''. At this point, in the early 2000s, he began to focus more on his theater work at The [[Purple Rose Theatre Company|Purple Rose Theatre]] as well as writing, starring, and directing the films ''[[Escanaba in da Moonlight]]'' and ''[[Super Sucker]]''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Daniels|first=Jeff|title=Escanaba in da Moonlight|date=February 9, 2001|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0180679/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_2|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Daniels|first=Jeff|title=Super Sucker|date=February 24, 2002|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0293624/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_1|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDaniels's next major film role would be in [[Clint Eastwood]]'s ''[[Blood Work (film)|Blood Work]]'', which received mixed reviews and was a commercial failure. He would rebound later that year with [[Stephen Daldry]]'s Academy Award-winning ''[[The Hours (film)|The Hours]]'' alongside [[Meryl Streep]], [[Julianne Moore]] and [[Nicole Kidman]]. The film was also a financial success, grossing well over $100 million. ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]'' followed in 2003, as did the action film ''[[I Witness]],'' which co-starred [[James Spader]]. Daniels then starred in ''[[Imaginary Heroes]]'' and the 2004 television film adaptation of fellow Michigander and friend [[Mitch Albom]]'s bestseller ''[[The Five People You Meet in Heaven]]''.<ref>{{Citation|last=Kramer|first=Lloyd|title=The Five People You Meet in Heaven|date=April 24, 2005|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0400435/|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe year 2005 proved to be a strong year for Daniels as he garnered notice as the star of the lauded [[Noah Baumbach]] film ''[[The Squid and the Whale]]'' with [[Laura Linney]]. Daniels received his third [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe nomination]] for the film, about a divorcing couple and the effect the split has on their children. That year Daniels also starred in the family film adaptation of ''[[Because of Winn-Dixie (film)|Because of Winn-Dixie]].'' He would round out the year with a supporting role in George Clooney's Oscar-nominated film ''[[Good Night and Good Luck]],'' starring [[David Straithairn]], [[Patricia Clarkson]], [[Robert Downey Jr.]], and [[Frank Langella]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Clooney|first=George|title=''Good Night, and Good Luck''|date=November 4, 2005|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0433383/awards|accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/good-night-and-good-luck-2005|title=Good Night, and Good Luck Movie Review (2005)|last=Ebert|first=Roger|website=www.rogerebert.com|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Daniels appeared in the [[Truman Capote]] biopic ''[[Infamous (film)|Infamous]]'' starring [[Toby Jones]], [[Sandra Bullock]], [[Gwyneth Paltrow]] and [[Sigourney Weaver]]. The film was compared to Bennett Miller's 2005 film ''[[Capote (film)|Capote]]'' starring [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]], [[Catherine Keener]] and [[Chris Cooper]].\n\nDaniels then starred in [[Barry Sonnenfeld]]'s family film ''[[RV (film)|RV]],'' alongside [[Robin Williams]] as the redneck comic foil to Williams' uptight business man. He also starred in two other independent films, ''[[Mama's Boy]]'' and ''[[The Lookout (2007 film)|The Lookout]],'' for which he was nominated for a [[Satellite Award for Best Supporting Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Satellite Award]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/awards/satellite-award-nominees-1117977011/|title=Satellite Award nominees|last=Staff|first=Variety|website=Variety|language=en-US|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe then took back-to-back supporting roles in political thrillers: ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]'' with [[Don Cheadle]] and ''[[State of Play (film)|State of Play]]'' with [[Russell Crowe]] and [[Rachel McAdams]]. Also in 2009, Daniels would appear in the indie hit ''[[Away We Go]]''. 2010 would be a slow year for Daniels. He continued his theater work and had a starring role in the little-seen indie ''[[Howl (2010 film)|Howl]],'' alongside [[James Franco]] as [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theatermania.com/los-angeles-theater/news/05-2010/howl-with-jeff-daniels-james-franco-mary-louise-pa_27095.html|title=Howl, with Jeff Daniels, James Franco, Mary-Louise Parker, Aaron Tveit, et al. to Open Outfest 2010|website=TheaterMania.com|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref> In 2012 Daniels became the new announcing voice for [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] with the [[iPhone 5]] ads.\n\nDaniels had a career resurgence with his turn in [[Aaron Sorkin]]'s [[HBO]] drama series ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]'' (2012\u20132014) as fictional news anchor Will McAvoy. The opening scene of the pilot episode, ''[[We Just Decided To]]'' in which Daniels gives a monologue on the state of American greatness went viral and has been viewed more than 13 million times.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ML3qYHWRIZk</ref> While the show received mixed reviews, Daniel's won the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] for the first season<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/emmys-newsrooms-jeff-daniels-surprise-634223</ref> The series ran for an additional two more seasons for which Daniels was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]]. The show also starred [[Emily Mortimer]], [[Sam Waterston]], [[Olivia Munn]], [[Allison Pill]], [[Dev Patel]], and [[Jane Fonda]].\n\nIn 2015, Daniels reunited with Sorkin in the biographical drama film ''[[Steve Jobs (film)|Steve Jobs]]'' with [[Michael Fassbender]], and [[Kate Winslet]]. He portrayed CEO [[John Sculley]]. Daniels starred alongside [[Michael Fassbender]], and [[Kate Winslet]] who both received [[Academy Award]] nominations for their performances. The film was directed by [[Academy Award]] winner [[Danny Boyle]], and written by [[Academy Award for Adapted Screenplay|Academy Award winner]] Aaron Sorkin. The film was a critical success earning an 86% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] with the consensus reading, \"Like the tech giant co-founded by its subject, Steve Jobs gathers brilliant people to deliver a product whose elegance belies the intricate complexities at its core.\"<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/steve_jobs_2015</ref> Sorkin won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Screenplay|Golden Globe]] for its Screenplay.<ref>https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/steve-jobs-wins-golden-globe-853443</ref>\n\nHe played David in ''[[The Divergent Series: Allegiant]]'' and was set to reprise the role in the planned ''The Divergent Series: Ascendant''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/jeff-daniels-joining-divergent-series-792184|title=Jeff Daniels Joining 'Divergent' Series in Key Role (Exclusive)\u2032|accessdate=April 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2014 he reprised his role as Harry Dunne in ''[[Dumb and Dumber To]]''.\n\nIn 2017, Daniels [[Hulu]]'s miniseries ''[[The Looming Tower]]'' which traces the rising threat of [[Osama bin Laden]] and [[Al-Qaeda]] in the late 1990s and how the rivalry between the [[FBI]] and [[CIA]] during that time may have inadvertently set the path for the tragedy of [[9/11]]. Daniels played [[John P. O'Neill|John O'Neill]], the chief of the [[New York City|New York]] FBI's [[Counter-terrorism]] Center. The ensemble included [[Bill Camp]], [[Michael Stuhlbarg]], and [[Peter Sarsgaard]].\nDaniels won widespread critical acclaim and received a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Best Actor in a Limited Series]].\n\nThat same year, Daniels starred in [[Netflix]]'s western miniseries ''[[Godless (TV series)|Godless]]'' where he portrayed the villain Frank Griffin. He starred alongside [[Michelle Dockery]], [[Merritt Wever]], and [[Sam Waterston]]. Daniels won critical praise for his performance and was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Limited Series or Movie|Supporting Actor in a Miniseries]] which he won.\n\n===Musical career===\nDaniels has focused on recording a number of songs that he has written throughout his life, apparently marking key moments. He has kept busy with frequent gigs and six full-length albums, ''Jeff Daniels Live and Unplugged'', ''Jeff Daniels Live at The Purple Rose Theater'', ''Grandfather's Hat'', ''Keep It Right Here'', ''Together Again'', and ''Days Like These''.<ref name=\"Outside acting\">{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/jeff-daniels-21090729#picking-up-steam |title=Jeff Daniels parties outside |last= |first= |date= |website=[[Biography.com]] |access-date=July 7, 2016}}</ref> Proceeds from the album sales benefit The [[Purple Rose Theatre Company|Purple Rose Theater]].<ref name=\"Outside acting\"/>\n\nDaniels was featured on the cover of the April\u2013May 2011 issue of ''Guitar Aficionado'' magazine<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.guitarplayer.com/guitaraficionado/jeff-daniels-march-2011-cover-story|title=Jeff Daniels: March/April 2011 Cover Story|work=GuitarPlayer.com|access-date=June 17, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> as well as the July\u2013August 2011 issue of ''[[Making Music (magazine)|Making Music]]'', where he discussed his experiences with music.\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1986, he moved back to his native Chelsea, Michigan, and as of 2016, he still primarily resides there.<ref>{{cite episode|series=[[The Late Show with Stephen Colbert]]|season=1|number=109|date=March 11, 2016|time=29:35|network=CBS|first=Jeff|last=Daniels|quote=For 30 years, I've lived in a little town called Chelsea, Michigan.}}</ref> In 1979, Daniels married his college sweetheart, a fellow Michigander also from Chelsea, MI, Kathleen Rosemary Treado.<ref name=wagc>{{cite web| url=http://wagcelebrity.com/bios/kathleen-rosemary-treado-jeff-daniels-wife-photos|title=Jeff Daniels' Wife and Children|website=wagcelebrity.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302115009/http://wagcelebrity.com/bios/kathleen-rosemary-treado-jeff-daniels-wife-photos|archivedate=March 2, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2013}}</ref> The couple have three children: Benjamin (born 1984), Lucas (born 1987), and Nellie (born 1990).<ref name=wagc/>\n\nDaniels has appeared as the TV spokesman for the [[Michigan Economic Development Corporation]], promoting Michigan's effectiveness in bringing in new companies, featured on [[CNBC]]. He was inducted into the [[Michigan Walk of Fame]] on May 25, 2006, in [[Lansing, Michigan]], and delivered the winter commencement address at the [[University of Michigan]] on December 20, 2009, at which he was granted an Honorary Doctorate in Fine Arts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lichterman|first=Joseph|title=Actor and Michigan native Jeff Daniels challenges graduates to make a difference at Winter Commencement|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/content/2009-winter-commencement|accessdate=May 19, 2010|newspaper=The Michigan Daily|date=December 20, 2009}}</ref> Daniels is a Democrat.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n<!--DO NOT USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY and WP:ACCESSIBILITY-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Ragtime (film)|Ragtime]]''\n| P. C. O'Donnell\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Terms of Endearment]]''\n| Flap Horton\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]''\n| Tom Baxter/Gil Shepherd\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Marie (film)|Marie]]''\n| Eddie Sisk\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Something Wild (1986 film)|Something Wild]]''\n| Charles Driggs\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Heartburn (film)|Heartburn]]''\n| Richard\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Radio Days]]''\n| Biff Baxter\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[The House on Carroll Street]]''\n| Cochran\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Sweet Hearts Dance]]''\n| Sam Manners\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Checking Out (1989 film)|Checking Out]]''\n| Ray Macklin\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Arachnophobia (film)|Arachnophobia]]''\n| Ross Jennings\n|\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Welcome Home, Roxy Carmichael]]''\n| Denton Webb\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[