te Martian (film)|My Favorite Martian]]''\n| Tim O'Hara\n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[It's the Rage (film)|It's the Rage]]''\n| Warren Harding\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Chasing Sleep]]''\n| Ed Saxon\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Cheaters (2000 film)|Cheaters]]''\n| Dr. Gerard Plecki\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Escanaba in da Moonlight]]''\n| Reuben Soady\n| Also co-writer and director\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Super Sucker]]''\n| Fred Barlow\n| Also co-writer and director\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Blood Work (film)|Blood Work]]''\n| Jasper \"Buddy\" Noone\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Hours (film)|The Hours]]''\n| Louis Waters\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]''\n| Lt. Colonel Joshua Chamberlain\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[I Witness]]''\n| James Rhodes\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Imaginary Heroes]]''\n| Ben Travis\n|\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Five People You Meet in Heaven#Film adaptation|The Five People You Meet in Heaven]]''\n| The Blue Man\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The Squid and the Whale]]''\n| Bernard Berkman\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Because of Winn-Dixie (film)|Because of Winn-Dixie]]''\n| The Preacher\n|\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Good Night, and Good Luck]]''\n| Sig Mickelson\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[RV (film)|RV]]''\n| Travis Gornicke\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Infamous (film)|Infamous]]''\n| [[Alvin Dewey]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Lookout (2007 film)|The Lookout]]''\n| Lewis\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Mama's Boy (film)|Mama's Boy]]''\n| Mert Rosenbloom\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[A Plumm Summer]]''\n| Narrator\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Space Chimps]]''\n| Zartog\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]''\n| Carter\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[State of Play (film)|State of Play]]''\n| Representative George Fergus\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The Answer Man (film)|The Answer Man]]''\n| Arlen Faber\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Away We Go (film)|Away We Go]]''\n| Jerry Farlander\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Paper Man (2009 film)|Paper Man]]''\n| Richard Dunn\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Howl (2010 film)|Howl]]''\n| Professor David Kirk\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Looper (film)|Looper]]''\n| Abe\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Quad (film)|Quad]]''\n| Mickey\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Dumb and Dumber To]]''\n| Harry Dunne\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Steve Jobs (film)|Steve Jobs]]''\n| [[John Sculley]]\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Martian (film)|The Martian]]''\n| Teddy Sanders\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Divergent Series: Allegiant]]''\n| David\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Catcher Was a Spy (film)|The Catcher Was a Spy]]''\n| [[William J. Donovan|Bill Donovan]]\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Guest Artist]]''\n|Joseph Harris\n|Also writer\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''\n| Neal Forrester\n| Episode: \"The Flight of the Jewels\"\n|-\n| 1980\n|''[[A Rumor of War (miniseries)|A Rumor of War]]''\n|Chaplain\n|miniseries\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Breaking Away (TV series)|Breaking Away]]''\n| College Kid\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 1982 \n|''[[Catalina C-Lab]]''\n|Rick Guthrie\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[American Playhouse]]''\n| Jed Jenkins\n| Episode: \"The Fifth of July\"\n|-\n| 1983\n|''[[An Invasion of Privacy]]''\n|Francis Ryan\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''No Place Like Home''\n| Mike\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Host\n| Episode: \"Jeff Daniels/[[Color Me Badd]]\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Teamster Boss: The Jackie Presser Story]]''\n| Tom Noonan\n| Television film\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Frasier]]''\n| Doug\n| Voice; Episode: \"Here's Looking at You\"\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''\n| Host\n| Episode: \"Jeff Daniels/[[Luscious Jackson]]\"\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Crossing (2000 film)|The Crossing]]''\n| [[George Washington]]\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Cheaters (2000 film)|Cheaters]]''\n| Dr. Gerard Plecki\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[The Goodbye Girl (2004 film)|The Goodbye Girl]]''\n| Elliot Garfield\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Sweet Nothing in My Ear]]''\n| Dan Miller\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]''\n| Will McAvoy\n| 25 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Godless (TV series)|Godless]]''\n| Frank Griffin\n| 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Looming Tower (miniseries)|The Looming Tower]]''\n| [[John P. O'Neill|John O\u2019Neill]]\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''The Emperor's Newest Clothes''\n| The Emperor\n| Voice; Television special\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Washington (miniseries)|Washington]]\n| Narrator\n| Miniseries\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Impractical Jokers]]\n| Himself\n| S08E25 \"Rock Bottom\", Challenge: \"Who Did The Fart?\"<ref>https://www.facebook.com/ImpracticalJokers/videos/impractical-jokers-who-did-the-fart-ft-jeff-daniels/203415921042708/?__so__=permalink&__rv__=related_videos</ref>\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[A Higher Loyalty (miniseries)|A Higher Loyalty]]''\n| [[James Comey]]\n| Upcoming miniseries\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Theatre\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''The Farm''\n| Arthur\n|rowspan=5| [[Circle Repertory Company|Circle Theatre]]\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''My Life''\n| Young Eddie\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''Lulu''\n| Schwarz / Mr. Hunidei\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''Two from the Late Show''\n| Nephew (Brontosaurus)\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n|rowspan=2|''[[Fifth of July]]''\n|rowspan=2|Jed Jenkins \n|\n|-\n| 1980\u201382\n| [[New Apollo Theatre]]\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Johnny Got His Gun#Adaptations|Johnny Got His Gun]]''\n| Joe Bonham\n|Circle Repertory Theatre\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]''\n| Andrei Sergeevich Prozorov\n| [[New York City Center]]\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n|''The Golden Age''\n| Tom \n| Jack Lawrence Theatre\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Lemon Sky]]''\n| Alan\n| [[McGinn/Cazale Theatre]]\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n|''Redwood Curtain''\n| Lyman\n| [[Brooks Atkinson Theatre]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n|''[[Blackbird (play)|Blackbird]]''\n| Ray\n|[[New York City Center]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\u201310\n|''[[God of Carnage]]''\n| Alan / Michael\n| [[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Tony Award nomination]]\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Blackbird (play)|Blackbird]]''\n| Ray\n| [[Belasco Theatre]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Tony Award nomination]]\n|-\n| 2018\u201319\n|''[[To Kill a Mockingbird (2018 play)|To Kill a Mockingbird]]''\n| [[Atticus Finch]]\n| [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theatre]]\n| [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Play|Tony Award nomination]]\n|}\n\n==[[Purple Rose Theatre Company]]==\n[[Image:Purple Rose Theater.JPG|thumb|Purple Rose Theatre]]\nThe ''Purple Rose Theatre Company'' (or '''PRTC''') was founded by Daniels in 1991. Originally known as the Garage Theatre, The Rose takes its name from [[Woody Allen]]'s 1985 film ''[[The Purple Rose of Cairo]]'', which starred Daniels and [[Mia Farrow]]. The [[theatre (structure)|theatre]] provides resources for training [[actors]], [[playwrights]], and other theatre artists residing in the [[Midwest]] and develops new plays based on life in the [[Great Lakes Basin]].<ref name=\"Detroit: Theater\"/> The main performance space and administrative offices occupy a building in Chelsea, Michigan, once owned by Daniels' grandfather. The theatre produces four shows a year on a 3/4 [[thrust stage]] in a 168-seat house. The PRTC is a 501(c)3 not-for-profit organization and operates under a Small Professional Theatre (SPT) Agreement with the [[Actors' Equity Association]] (AEA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.purplerosetheatre.org/participate/auditions|title=Auditions|website=The Purple Rose Theater Company|publisher=The Purple Rose Theater Company|access-date=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Apprentice program===\nThe Purple Rose offers a year-long [[apprenticeship]] program for young artists entering a career in [[theatre]]. Apprentices are paid a modest stipend and work as many as 80 hours per week gaining experience in lighting, sound, stage management, design, set construction, and administrative/box office work. The seven apprentices also maintain and clean the theatre's facilities. The program was inspired by Daniels' experience as an apprentice with the [[Circle Repertory Company]] in [[New York City]].\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Jeff Daniels}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jeff Daniels}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.jeffdaniels.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|1099}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|15977}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Jeff Daniels|Awards for Jeff Daniels]]\n| list  =\n{{EmmyAward DramaLeadActor 2001\u20132025}}\n{{EmmyAward MiniseriesSupportingActor}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daniels, Jeff}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American United Methodists]]\n[[Category:Central Michigan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan Democrats]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Athens, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Obie Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actor in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or Movie Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Chelsea, Michigan]]\n[[Category:People from Clarke County, Georgia]]\n", "name_user": "Sunshineisles2", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeff_Daniels"}
{"title_page": "Egremont railway station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in Cumbria, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name = Egremont\n | gridref = NY010111\n | coordinates = {{coord|54.4861|-3.5289|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | image_name = \n | caption = \n | original    = [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n | pregroup    = LNWR & FR Joint Railway\n | postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n | locale = [[Egremont, Cumbria]]\n | borough = [[Borough of Copeland|Copeland]]\n | platforms = 2{{sfn|Anderson|2002|p=310}}\n | years = 1 July 1857\n | events = Opened\n | years1 = 7 January 1935\n | events1 = Closed to passengers\n | years2 = 11 March 1940\n | events2 = Reopened to workmen's trains{{sfn|Croughton|Kidner|Young|1982|p=142}}\n | years3 = 8 April 1940\n | events3 = Closed\n | years4 = 6 May 1946\n | events4 = Reopened\n | years5 = 16 June 1947\n | events5 = Closed, but remained open for workmen's trains{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=90}}\n | years6 = 6 September 1965\n | events6 = Workmen's trained ended{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}}\n | years7 = 11 December 1969\n | events7 = School service ended, station closed{{sfn|Quayle|2007|pp=87-8}}\n}}\n{{Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway RDT|collapse=yes}}\n'''Egremont railway station''' was built by the [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]] as the first southern terminus of what would become the {{rws|Moor Row}} to {{rws|Sellafield}} branch. In 1878 the company was bought out by the [[London and North Western Railway|LNWR]] and [[Furness Railway]] who operated the line jointly until grouping in 1923.\n\nThe station was towards the northern end of the town, in [[Cumbria]], England.{{sfn|Smith|Turner|2012|loc=Map 26}}{{sfn|Jowett|2000|loc=Map 36}}\n\n==History==\nThe line was one of the fruits of the rapid industrialisation of West Cumberland in the second half of the nineteenth century, opening to passengers on 1 July 1857.\n\nThe station remained as the railway's southern terminus until 1869 when the company, in partnership with the [[Furness Railway]], built a southern extension from Egremont to the coast line at {{rws|Sellafield}}, with an intermediate station at {{rws|Beckermet}}. This enabled traffic from the Cleator Moor and Rowrah areas, especially iron ore, to move much more readily southwards.\n\n==Services==\nIn 1922 eight northbound passenger trains left Egremont, two connected with trains to {{rws|Whitehaven}} at {{rws|Moor Row}}, all the others continued there without a change. A Saturdays Only evening train terminated at Moor Row. The southbound service was similar. There were no Sunday trains.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|p=510}}\n\nThe LNWR and Furness Joint Railway divided traffic responsibilities so that passenger traffic through the station was usually worked by the Furness Railway.{{sfn|McGowan Gradon|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Quayle|2007|p=38}}\n\nA three times a day unadvertised workmen's service from {{rws|Moor Row}} to {{rws|Beckermet Mines}} began on 15 January 1912, calling at {{rws|Woodend}}, Egremont and {{rws|St Thomas Cross Platform}}.{{sfn|Robinson|1989|p=39}} It is not yet clear when this came to an end or if other services were provided.\n\nGoods traffic was typical of an industrial area, sustaining sidings and goods depots long after passenger services were withdrawn.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|p=79}}\n\nMineral traffic was the dominant flow, though this was subject to considerable fluctuation with trade cycles. A considerable amount of iron ore travelled south through and from Egremont bound for the furnaces of Millom and Barrow-in-Furness.\n\nStations and signalling along the line south of Rowrah were changed during the Joint regime to conform to Furness Railway standards.<ref>[http://www.cumberlandarchives.co.uk/content/view/239/48/1/13/ W McGowan Gradon's 1942 Furness Railway study, via ''cumberlandarchives.co.uk'']</ref>\n\n==Rundown and closure==\nThe station closed on 7 January 1935 when normal passenger traffic ended along the line.\n\nLife flickered briefly in Spring 1940 when workmen's trains were reinstated to support a period of high activity building the Royal Ordnance Factory at Drigg, but that lasted less than a month.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}}\n\nA public Sellafield-Egremont-Moor Row-Whitehaven service was reinstated on 6 May 1946, only to be \"suspended\" on 16 June 1947, a victim of the post-war fuel crisis. Bradshaw still listed the service as Suspended in 1949.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}} It was never reinstated.{{sfn|Marshall|1981|page=116}}\n\nWorkmen's trains to Sellafield ended on 6 September 1965.{{sfn|Suggitt|2008|p=56}}\n\nRemarkably, a wholly new unadvertised passenger service started in September 1964, conveying pupils to Wyndham School in Egremont from {{rws|Seascale}} in the morning then home after school. Initially this comprised eight steam-hauled carriages, ending typically formed of a pair of Derby Lightweight 2-car units. Sources differ on when this service ended:- 3 March 1969{{sfn|Croughton|Kidner|Young|1982|p=142}} or 11 December 1969.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|pp=87-8}}\n\nIron Ore from Beckermet Mines continued to pass through the station site until 1980, after which the line was closed and lifted.{{sfn|Welbourne|2010|p=112}}{{sfn|Marsh|Garbutt|2002|p=148}}\n\n==Afterlife==\nBy 2013 satellite images appeared to show that the route through Egremont was a sliver of Public Open Space.\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous={{rws|Woodend}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|next={{rws|St Thomas Cross Platform}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|route=[[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n|col={{LNWR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n* [[Furness Railway]]\n* [[Cleator and Workington Junction Railway]]\n* [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite journal |last=Anderson |first=Paul |editor1-first=Chris |editor1-last=Hawkins |date=April 2002 |title=Dog in the Manger? The Track of the Ironmasters |journal=British Railways Illustrated |volume=11| issue= 7 |publisher=Irwell Press Ltd |location= Clophill |issn= |ref=harv }}\n* {{Bradshaw-1922July}}\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Croughton |first1=Godfrey |last2=Kidner |first2=Roger W. |last3=Young |first3=Alan |title=Private and Untimetabled Railway Stations, Halts and Stopping Places X 43 |year=1982 |publisher=The Oakwood Press |location=Headington, Oxford |isbn=0 85361 281 1 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Jowett-Atlas}}\n* {{cite book |last=McGowan Gradon |first=W. |title=The Track of the Ironmasters: A History of the Cleator and Workington Junction Railway |year=2004 |origyear=1952 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location=Grange-over-Sands |isbn=0-9540232-2-6 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Marsh |first1=John |last2=Garbutt |first2=John |title=Images of Cumbrian Railways |year=April 2002 |publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |location= |isbn=0-7509-2834-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Quayle |first=Howard |title=Whitehaven: The Railways and Waggonways of a Unique Cumberland Port |year=2007 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location=Pinner |isbn=978-0-9540232-5-6 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Robinson |first=Peter W. |editor1-first=Michael |editor1-last=Peascod |date=February 1989 |title=Workmen's Trains to Beckermet Mines |journal=Cumbrian Railways |volume=4| issue= 3 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location= Pinner |issn=1466-6812 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Smith|first1=Paul|last2=Turner|first2=Keith|title=Railway Atlas Then and Now|year=2012|publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]]|isbn=978 0 7110 3695 6 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Suggitt |first=Gordon |title=Lost Railways of Cumbria (Railway Series) |year=2008 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=978-1-84674-107-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Welbourn |first=Nigel |title=Lost Lines: Joint Railways |year=September 2010 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=978-0-7110-3428-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas And Gazetteer|origyear=1958 |year=1997 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |location=Shepperton | isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Atterbury |first=Paul |title=Along Lost Lines |year=2009 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0-7153-2706-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Bairstow |first=Martin |title=Railways In The Lake District |year=1995 |publisher=Martin Bairstow |location= |isbn=1-871944-11-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |title=Rails through Lakeland: An Illustrated Journey of the Workington-Cockermouth-Keswick-Penrith Railway 1847-1972 |last=Bowtell |first=Harold D. |year=1989 |publisher=Silverling Publishing Ltd |location=Wyre, Lancashire |isbn=0-947971-26-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Joy |first=David |title=Lake Counties (Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain) |year=1983 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=094653702X |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Marshall |first=John |title=Forgotten Railways: North West England |year=1981 |publisher=[[David & Charles]] |location=Newton Abbot |isbn=0 7153 8003 6 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Western |first=Robert |title=The Cockermouth, Keswick and Penrith Railway OL113 |year=2001 |publisher=Oakwood Press |location=Usk |isbn=0-85361-564-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.railscot.co.uk/Whitehaven_Cleator_and_Egremont_Railway/index.php Map of the line with photos, via ''RAILSCOT'']\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/view/102340902 The station as the line's southern terminus on an 1867 OS map, via ''National Library of Scotland'']\n*[http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=16&lat=54.4865&lon=-3.5294&layers=6 The station on overlain OS maps surveyed from 1898, via ''National Library of Scotland'']\n*[http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#301,510,1 The station on a 1948 OS Map, via ''npe maps'']\n*[http://www.cumbria-railways.co.uk/ The railways of Cumbria, via ''Cumbrian Railways Association'']\n*[http://cumbrianrailways.zenfolio.com/ Photos of Cumbrian railways, via ''Cumbrian Railways Association'']\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160322115319/http://cumbrianrailways.org.uk/Railways_of_Cumbria.php The railways of Cumbria, via ''Railways_of_Cumbria'']\n*[http://www.cumbria-industries.org.uk/a-z-of-industries/railways/ Cumbrian Industrial History, via ''Cumbria Industrial History Society'']\n*[http://www.railwaycodes.org.uk/ELRs/_mileages/W/WET.txt The line's and station's Engineer's Line References, via ''railwaycodes.org.uk'']\n*[http://www.sixbellsjunction.co.uk/ Furness Railtour using many West Cumberland lines 5 September 1954, via ''sixbellsjunction'']\n*[http://thecumbriafilmarchive.com/#/cumbrias-lost-lines/4545854062 A video tour-de-force of the region's closed lines, via ''cumbriafilmarchive'']\n*[https://celestialearthminerals.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/Hematite-08-2007.pdf Haematite, via ''earthminerals'']\n\n{{Closed stations Cumbria}}\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Cumbria]]\n\n[[Category:Beeching closures in England]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1857]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1947]]\n[[Category:1857 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Egremont, Cumbria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in Cumbria, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name = Egremont\n | gridref = NY010111\n | coordinates = {{coord|54.4861|-3.5289|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | image_name = \n | caption = \n | original    = [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n | pregroup    = LNWR & FR Joint Railway\n | postgroup   = [[London, Midland and Scottish Railway]]\n | locale = [[Egremont, Cumbria]]\n | borough = [[Borough of Copeland|Copeland]]\n | platforms = 2{{sfn|Anderson|2002|p=310}}\n | years = 1 July 1857\n | events = Opened\n | years1 = 7 January 1935\n | events1 = Closed to passengers\n | years2 = 11 March 1940\n | events2 = Reopened to workmen's trains{{sfn|Croughton|Kidner|Young|1982|p=142}}\n | years3 = 8 April 1940\n | events3 = Closed\n | years4 = 6 May 1946\n | events4 = Reopened\n | years5 = 16 June 1947\n | events5 = Closed, but remained open for workmen's trains{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=90}}\n | years6 = 6 September 1965\n | events6 = Workmen's trained ended{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}}\n | years7 = 11 December 1969\n | events7 = School service ended, station closed{{sfn|Quayle|2007|pp=87-8}}\n}}\n{{Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway RDT|collapse=yes}}\n'''Egremont railway station''' was built by the [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]] as the first southern terminus of what would become the {{rws|Moor Row}} to {{rws|Sellafield}} branch. In 1878 the company was bought out by the [[London and North Western Railway|LNWR]] and [[Furness Railway]] who operated the line jointly until grouping in 1923.\n\nThe station was towards the northern end of the town, in [[Cumbria]], England.{{sfn|Smith|Turner|2012|loc=Map 26}}{{sfn|Jowett|2000|loc=Map 36}}\n\n==History==\nThe line was one of the fruits of the rapid industrialisation of West Cumberland in the second half of the nineteenth century, opening to passengers on 1 July 1857.\n\nThe station remained as the railway's southern terminus until 1869 when the company, in partnership with the [[Furness Railway]], built a southern extension from Egremont to the coast line at {{rws|Sellafield}}, with an intermediate station at {{rws|Beckermet}}. This enabled traffic from the Cleator Moor and Rowrah areas, especially iron ore, to move much more readily southwards.\n\n==Services==\nIn 1922 eight northbound passenger trains left Egremont, two connected with trains to {{rws|Whitehaven}} at {{rws|Moor Row}}, all the others continued there without a change. A Saturdays Only evening train terminated at Moor Row. The southbound service was similar. There were no Sunday trains.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|p=510}}\n\nThe LNWR and Furness Joint Railway divided traffic responsibilities so that passenger traffic through the station was usually worked by the Furness Railway.{{sfn|McGowan Gradon|2004|p=12}}{{sfn|Quayle|2007|p=38}}\n\nA three times a day unadvertised workmen's service from {{rws|Moor Row}} to {{rws|Beckermet Mines}} began on 15 January 1912, calling at {{rws|Woodend}}, Egremont and {{rws|St Thomas Cross Platform}}.{{sfn|Robinson|1989|p=39}} It is not yet clear when this came to an end or if other services were provided.\n\nGoods traffic was typical of an industrial area, sustaining sidings and goods depots long after passenger services were withdrawn.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|p=79}}\n\nMineral traffic was the dominant flow, though this was subject to considerable fluctuation with trade cycles. A considerable amount of iron ore travelled south through and from Egremont bound for the furnaces of Millom and Barrow-in-Furness.\n\nStations and signalling along the line south of Rowrah were changed during the Joint regime to conform to Furness Railway standards.<ref>[http://www.cumberlandarchives.co.uk/content/view/239/48/1/13/ W McGowan Gradon's 1942 Furness Railway study, via ''cumberlandarchives.co.uk'']</ref>\n\n==Rundown and closure==\nThe station closed on 7 January 1935 when normal passenger traffic ended along the line.\n\nLife flickered briefly in Spring 1940 when workmen's trains were reinstated to support a period of high activity building the Royal Ordnance Factory at Drigg, but that lasted less than a month.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}}\n\nA public Sellafield-Egremont-Moor Row-Whitehaven service was reinstated on 6 May 1946, only to be \"suspended\" on 16 June 1947, a victim of the post-war fuel crisis. Bradshaw still listed the service as Suspended in 1949.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|page=87}} It was never reinstated.{{sfn|Marshall|1981|page=116}}\n\nWorkmen's trains to Sellafield ended on 6 September 1965.{{sfn|Suggitt|2008|p=56}}\n\nRemarkably, a wholly new unadvertised passenger service started in September 1964, conveying pupils to Wyndham School in Egremont from {{rws|Seascale}} in the morning then home after school. Initially this comprised eight steam-hauled carriages, ending typically formed of a pair of Derby Lightweight 2-car units. Sources differ on when this service ended:- 3 March 1969{{sfn|Croughton|Kidner|Young|1982|p=142}} or 11 December 1969.{{sfn|Quayle|2007|pp=87-8}}\n\nIron Ore from Beckermet Mines continued to pass through the station site until 1980, after which the line was closed and lifted.{{sfn|Welbourne|2010|p=112}}{{sfn|Marsh|Garbutt|2002|p=148}}\n\n==Afterlife==\nBy 2013 satellite images appeared to show that the route through Egremont was a sliver of Public Open Space.\n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous={{rws|Woodend}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|next={{rws|St Thomas Cross Platform}}<br><small>Line and station closed</small>\n|route=[[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n|col={{LNWR colour}} }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n* [[Furness Railway]]\n* [[Cleator and Workington Junction Railway]]\n* [[Whitehaven, Cleator and Egremont Railway]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite journal |last=Anderson |first=Paul |editor1-first=Chris |editor1-last=Hawkins |date=April 2002 |title=Dog in the Manger? The Track of the Ironmasters |journal=British Railways Illustrated |volume=11| issue= 7 |publisher=Irwell Press Ltd |location= Clophill |issn= |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Bradshaw|title=Bradshaw's July 1922 Railway Guide (reprint)|year=1986|origyear=1922|publisher=Guild Publishing London|ref=harv }}\n* {{Butt-Stations}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Croughton |first1=Godfrey |last2=Kidner |first2=Roger W. |last3=Young |first3=Alan |title=Private and Untimetabled Railway Stations, Halts and Stopping Places X 43 |year=1982 |publisher=The Oakwood Press |location=Headington, Oxford |isbn=0 85361 281 1 |ref=harv }}\n* {{Jowett-Atlas}}\n* {{cite book |last=McGowan Gradon |first=W. |title=The Track of the Ironmasters: A History of the Cleator and Workington Junction Railway |year=2004 |origyear=1952 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location=Grange-over-Sands |isbn=0-9540232-2-6 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Marsh |first1=John |last2=Garbutt |first2=John |title=Images of Cumbrian Railways |year=April 2002 |publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd |location= |isbn=0-7509-2834-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Quayle |first=Howard |title=Whitehaven: The Railways and Waggonways of a Unique Cumberland Port |year=2007 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location=Pinner |isbn=978-0-9540232-5-6 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite journal |last=Robinson |first=Peter W. |editor1-first=Michael |editor1-last=Peascod |date=February 1989 |title=Workmen's Trains to Beckermet Mines |journal=Cumbrian Railways |volume=4| issue= 3 |publisher=Cumbrian Railways Association |location= Pinner |issn=1466-6812 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Smith|first1=Paul|last2=Turner|first2=Keith|title=Railway Atlas Then and Now|year=2012|publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]]|isbn=978 0 7110 3695 6 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Suggitt |first=Gordon |title=Lost Railways of Cumbria (Railway Series) |year=2008 |publisher=Countryside Books |location=Newbury |isbn=978-1-84674-107-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Welbourn |first=Nigel |title=Lost Lines: Joint Railways |year=September 2010 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=978-0-7110-3428-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |title=British Railways Pre-Grouping Atlas And Gazetteer|origyear=1958 |year=1997 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing]] |location=Shepperton | isbn=0-7110-0320-3 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |l